export const QUESTIONS = {"office_professional":[[{"phase":"situation","question":"When your firm takes on a new client engagement — whether it's advisory, HR, or consulting — what does your standard contract or engagement letter look like? Is it something your team drafted in-house, or has an attorney reviewed it?","goodResponse":"Most professional service firms are running on templated agreements they wrote years ago without legal review. That's where liability quietly accumulates. What does your current engagement letter cover in terms of scope limitations and liability caps?","badResponse":"We draft and review professional services contracts. It's something we do for a lot of firms like yours.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you ever had a client dispute the scope of your work — or push back on an invoice — and realized your engagement letter wasn't specific enough to back you up?","goodResponse":"Scope creep and invoice disputes are the most common pain point I hear from professional service firms, and they almost always trace back to engagement language that's too vague. Has anything like that happened recently?","badResponse":"We write tight engagement letters that protect firms like yours from scope disputes.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a client challenge escalated and you had to bring in outside counsel to defend your position — but your own engagement letter was ambiguous — what's the realistic worst-case exposure for your firm, financially and reputationally?","goodResponse":"The cost of a single disputed engagement that goes sideways almost always dwarfs the cost of getting your agreements properly drafted upfront. That math is worth running before you're in the middle of it.","badResponse":"Bad contracts lead to legal fees and lost clients. Let's fix yours.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your engagement letters, NDAs, and service agreements were all airtight and reviewed by counsel who understands professional services liability — how would that change your confidence when onboarding high-value clients?","goodResponse":"That's the shift we see every time. Firms stop hedging on pricing and stop over-delivering out of fear when they know their contracts actually protect them. Let me walk you through what a contract package review looks like.","badResponse":"We can review your whole contract stack. It's usually a half-day project.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"Do you have a non-solicitation or non-compete framework in place for your employees or partners — something that's been reviewed for enforceability in your state in the last couple of years?","goodResponse":"Non-compete law has shifted dramatically in several states, and agreements written even three years ago may be unenforceable today. What does your current employee agreement stack look like?","badResponse":"We update and draft employment agreements, including non-competes and NDAs.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Has a key employee or partner ever left and immediately started working for a competitor or soliciting your clients — and your agreement either wasn't enforceable or wasn't specific enough to stop it?","goodResponse":"That situation is more common than firms want to admit, and it's almost always avoidable with the right agreement structure. What happened with your clients or IP when that person left?","badResponse":"We draft enforceable non-solicitation agreements that actually hold up.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a departing employee took a book of clients worth — let's say — 20 percent of your revenue, and you had no legal recourse because the agreement wouldn't hold up, what does that do to your firm's growth trajectory for the next two or three years?","goodResponse":"Losing even one anchor client relationship to a competitor because of a weak non-solicitation is the kind of loss that compounds. You lose the revenue, the referrals, and the relationships they brought with them.","badResponse":"That's a major risk. Better agreements prevent it.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If every person in your firm — partners, senior staff, contractors — signed updated agreements that were actually enforceable and tailored to your state's current law, how much more secure would you feel about your client relationships and proprietary methods?","goodResponse":"That peace of mind is the real ROI. Let me show you what a full employment agreement audit and rewrite looks like for a firm at your size — it's usually a one-time project with recurring value.","badResponse":"We do employment agreement audits. It's a flat-fee engagement.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"When you bring on a new business partner or equity stakeholder — or restructure ownership — do you have an operating agreement or shareholder agreement that spells out buyout terms, decision rights, and what happens in a dispute?","goodResponse":"Ownership structures that aren't spelled out in a formal agreement are one of the leading causes of firm dissolution. Most partners assume alignment until there's a real conflict. What does your current governance structure look like?","badResponse":"We draft operating agreements and partnership structures for professional service firms.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you ever had a disagreement with a co-owner or partner about direction, compensation, or an exit — and realized there was no written process in place to resolve it without lawyers and courts?","goodResponse":"Partner disputes without a governing agreement are where firms die. Even good partnerships hit friction when there's no documented process for making hard decisions. What's the most contentious ownership issue your firm has faced?","badResponse":"We write operating agreements that prevent those disputes from spiraling.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a partner dispute escalated into litigation without a clear governing agreement — disrupting operations, alarming clients, and potentially forcing a dissolution — what's the human and financial cost of that scenario for everyone involved?","goodResponse":"The most expensive legal bill most business owners ever see is a partnership dissolution that could have been avoided with a well-drafted operating agreement. The legal cost of prevention is a fraction of the cure.","badResponse":"Partnership disputes get expensive fast. Good agreements prevent them.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your ownership structure was fully documented — with clear governance, buyout mechanics, and dispute resolution built in — how would that change the conversations you have with current or prospective partners about the future of the firm?","goodResponse":"That clarity attracts better partners and makes every ownership conversation less stressful. Let me outline what a governance document package looks like for a firm your size.","badResponse":"We draft operating agreements and shareholder structures. Let's set up a scope call.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}]],"tech_company":[[{"phase":"situation","question":"When you onboard a new SaaS customer or enterprise client, what does your subscription agreement or master service agreement look like — is it something your team built, or has outside counsel reviewed it for IP and liability exposure?","goodResponse":"Tech companies grow fast and their contracts often don't keep up. The SaaS agreements that worked at $500K ARR tend to create real liability exposure at $5M ARR — especially around uptime, data responsibility, and IP ownership. What's your current MSA structure?","badResponse":"We review and draft SaaS agreements and MSAs for tech companies.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you ever had an enterprise prospect stall or kill a deal because their legal team flagged something in your contract — indemnification language, data processing terms, or IP assignment clauses — that you couldn't quickly resolve?","goodResponse":"That's one of the most common growth blockers I hear from scaling SaaS companies — the contract becomes the deal killer, not the product. How long did that deal stall, and did it close?","badResponse":"We fix the contract language that kills enterprise deals. It's a very solvable problem.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If enterprise deals are stalling in legal review for weeks while your sales team waits — and some are dying on the table — what does that do to your average sales cycle length and your ARR growth target for the year?","goodResponse":"Every week a contract sits in legal review is a week of deferred revenue, and it compounds across your entire pipeline. A clean, enterprise-ready contract set typically cuts legal review time by 60 to 70 percent.","badResponse":"Slow contracts hurt ARR. We fix that.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If you had a contract package — MSA, DPA, SLA, and acceptable use policy — that was pre-negotiated to close enterprise deals faster, how would that change your sales team's ability to hit their number this quarter?","goodResponse":"That's the outcome: contracts that close faster and protect you better. Let me walk you through what a SaaS contract package review and redraft looks like — most companies complete it in three to four weeks.","badResponse":"We build enterprise-ready contract packages for SaaS companies. Let's scope it.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"How are you handling IP assignment agreements for your engineers and contractors — especially contractors who are building core product features? Are those agreements in place and signed before work starts?","goodResponse":"Contractor IP assignment is one of the most overlooked risks in tech companies. If a contractor builds something core to your product without a proper work-for-hire or IP assignment agreement, they may own a piece of your product. What does your contractor agreement currently say about IP?","badResponse":"We draft IP assignment agreements and work-for-hire clauses for tech companies.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you ever had an investor or acquirer's due diligence process surface questions about IP ownership — specifically around contractor contributions — that you couldn't answer cleanly?","goodResponse":"IP ownership questions in due diligence are one of the most common deal complications in tech M&A and fundraising. If the chain of title isn't clean, it can reduce your valuation or kill the deal. Has this come up in any of your conversations with investors?","badResponse":"IP gaps in due diligence kill deals. We close those gaps proactively.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a future fundraising round or acquisition surfaces a contractor IP issue that delays or discounts the deal — and the fix requires months of legal work to clean up — what's the downstream cost to your founders and early investors?","goodResponse":"I've seen IP chain-of-title issues knock 10 to 20 percent off acquisition valuations because the buyer has to price in the risk. The cost of cleaning this up before a transaction is always lower than the cost of discovering it during one.","badResponse":"IP issues in due diligence are expensive. Let's fix them now.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If every engineer and contractor who touched your codebase had a current, clean IP assignment agreement on file — and you could produce that documentation in 24 hours during due diligence — how would that change the confidence investors or acquirers have in your company?","goodResponse":"Clean IP documentation is a trust signal that sophisticated buyers and investors notice immediately. Let me walk you through a standard IP audit and remediation project — most companies complete it in four to six weeks.","badResponse":"We do IP audits and clean up contractor agreement stacks. It's usually a four-week project.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"What does your data privacy compliance posture look like right now — are you operating under a privacy policy and data processing framework that's been reviewed against GDPR, CCPA, or any state-level privacy laws that apply to your user base?","goodResponse":"Privacy law has gotten significantly more complex in the last three years, and enforcement is ramping up. Most tech companies are running on policies that were written when GDPR first passed and haven't been updated since. What markets are your users or customers in?","badResponse":"We help tech companies build out their privacy compliance framework.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you received any GDPR data subject requests, CCPA opt-out requests, or privacy inquiries from users that your team wasn't sure how to respond to — or responded to inconsistently?","goodResponse":"Inconsistent handling of data subject requests is where enforcement actions and class actions often start. Even if you've never had a formal complaint, the liability is accumulating. How does your team currently handle those requests when they come in?","badResponse":"We build the privacy response processes that keep companies out of regulatory trouble.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a privacy regulator or plaintiff's attorney reviewed your data handling practices and found gaps between your published policy and your actual practices — what's the exposure in terms of fines, litigation costs, and reputational damage to your brand?","goodResponse":"GDPR fines can reach four percent of global annual turnover, and class action exposure under CCPA is real and growing. The cost of a privacy enforcement action almost always exceeds the cost of building a proper compliance framework by a factor of ten or more.","badResponse":"Privacy fines are real and large. Compliance is much cheaper.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If you had a current, legally reviewed privacy policy, internal data handling procedures, and a documented response process for data subject requests — how would that change your confidence when enterprise prospects or regulators ask about your data practices?","goodResponse":"Enterprise buyers are running privacy due diligence more rigorously than ever, and having clean documentation is increasingly a sales prerequisite. Let me outline what a privacy compliance review and framework build looks like for a company your size.","badResponse":"We do privacy compliance reviews and build the documentation. Let's scope it.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}]],"healthcare":[[{"phase":"situation","question":"When you bring on a new employee or credentialed provider, what does your employment agreement or independent contractor agreement look like — specifically around non-solicitation, patient record ownership, and restrictive covenants?","goodResponse":"Healthcare employment agreements have some unique wrinkles — particularly around patient record ownership and post-departure patient solicitation. Courts have treated these clauses differently than standard employment covenants. What does your current agreement cover?","badResponse":"We draft healthcare employment agreements that address provider departures and patient solicitation.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you ever had a provider leave your practice and start soliciting patients directly — or join a competing practice nearby — and found that your non-solicitation clause either wasn't enforceable or wasn't specific enough to stop it?","goodResponse":"Provider departures with patient solicitation are one of the most damaging events for a healthcare practice, and they happen more often than practice owners expect. What was the impact on your patient panel and revenue when that happened?","badResponse":"We write enforceable non-solicitation clauses for healthcare employment agreements.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a departing provider took even 15 percent of your active patient panel to a competing practice, and you had no legal recourse because the agreement didn't hold up — what does that do to your collections and the long-term value of your practice?","goodResponse":"Losing patient relationships to a departing provider is one of the fastest ways to erode practice value, and it's almost always avoidable with properly structured agreements. The practice value hit compounds if you're thinking about a sale or transition in the next few years.","badResponse":"Provider non-solicitation protects your practice value. Let's make sure yours works.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If every provider agreement in your practice had enforceable non-solicitation language, clear patient record ownership terms, and buyout clauses that protected the practice — how would that change your confidence when bringing on new providers?","goodResponse":"That security changes the dynamic of every provider onboarding conversation. Let me walk you through a provider agreement audit and what a standard healthcare employment package covers.","badResponse":"We audit and redraft provider agreements for healthcare practices. It's a focused engagement.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"Do you have a current Business Associate Agreement in place with every vendor that touches protected health information — your EHR, billing company, IT provider, and any cloud services your practice uses?","goodResponse":"BAA compliance is one of the most common gaps we find when we review healthcare practice relationships. A lot of vendors will sign them if asked, but practices often don't ask. Which vendors are you currently relying on that handle PHI?","badResponse":"We ensure all your vendor BAAs are in place and compliant — it's a HIPAA requirement that's commonly overlooked.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you had a HIPAA audit, a patient privacy complaint, or a breach notification situation that revealed gaps in your Business Associate Agreement coverage or your internal privacy policies?","goodResponse":"HIPAA audits are becoming more targeted, especially for practices that have experienced breaches or complaints. Even without a formal audit, the liability from missing BAAs is real. What triggered the situation you're describing?","badResponse":"HIPAA gaps create liability. We find and close them proactively.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If OCR found that you were sharing PHI with a vendor who didn't have a signed BAA in place — and that finding triggered a corrective action plan and civil monetary penalties — what's the realistic financial and operational exposure for your practice?","goodResponse":"OCR penalties for HIPAA violations range from $100 to $50,000 per violation, and they compound per incident. More importantly, corrective action plans consume enormous amounts of staff time and administrative bandwidth. The cost of prevention is a fraction of either of those outcomes.","badResponse":"HIPAA fines are serious. A full BAA audit is inexpensive by comparison.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If every vendor relationship that touches your PHI was covered by a current, executed BAA, and your internal privacy policies were reviewed and documented — how would that change your risk posture going into a potential audit or payer credentialing review?","goodResponse":"Clean HIPAA documentation is increasingly a credentialing and contracting requirement as well as a regulatory one. Let me walk you through what a HIPAA compliance review and BAA audit looks like for a practice your size.","badResponse":"We do HIPAA audits and BAA reviews. It's usually a two-to-three week engagement.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"If you're thinking about a practice transition in the next five to ten years — whether that's a sale, a merger, or bringing in a partner — do you have the shareholder agreement, operating agreement, and valuation methodology in place to facilitate that cleanly?","goodResponse":"Practice succession and transition planning is one of the most under-prepared areas for healthcare practice owners. The legal structure you have in place now either makes that transition smooth or creates expensive complications later. What does your ownership structure look like currently?","badResponse":"We help healthcare practices structure for sale, merger, or partner transitions.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you looked at your current operating agreement to see whether it actually addresses how a buyout would work — the valuation method, payment terms, and what happens if a partner wants out or passes away?","goodResponse":"Most healthcare practice operating agreements are thin on succession mechanics, and that's usually fine until it isn't. The moment a partner wants out or a life event forces the question, the gaps become very expensive. What does yours say about buyout terms?","badResponse":"We write practice operating agreements with real succession provisions built in.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a partner dispute or unplanned exit forced a practice dissolution or fire-sale transaction because there was no buyout mechanism in place — and you received significantly less than the practice was worth — what would that mean for your retirement timeline?","goodResponse":"For most healthcare providers, the practice is the largest asset in their retirement plan. A forced or unplanned transition without proper legal structure is one of the most common ways that asset gets severely undervalued. That's a risk worth addressing well in advance.","badResponse":"Practice transitions without legal structure destroy value. Let's protect yours.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your practice had a fully documented operating agreement with buyout mechanics, a current valuation methodology on file, and a succession roadmap — how would that change your ability to bring in a partner, plan an exit, or respond to an acquisition offer?","goodResponse":"That documentation puts you in a position of strength in any ownership transition conversation. Let me outline what a practice succession legal package looks like and how we structure the engagement.","badResponse":"We build practice succession legal packages. It's one of our most impactful service areas.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}]],"retail_food":[[{"phase":"situation","question":"When you signed your commercial lease — or if you're looking at a new location — did you have an attorney review the terms before you committed? Things like rent escalation clauses, CAM charges, exclusive use provisions, and personal guarantee language?","goodResponse":"Commercial leases for food and retail businesses are some of the most landlord-favorable documents out there, and most owners sign them without legal review. The terms that hurt you most — personal guarantees and CAM charges — are often negotiable if you know what to ask for. What's your current lease situation?","badResponse":"We review commercial leases and negotiate terms for retail and food businesses.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you ever had a landlord hit you with unexpected CAM charges, a lease renewal disagreement, or a personal guarantee enforcement situation that you weren't prepared for legally?","goodResponse":"CAM reconciliation disputes and lease renewal conflicts are the most common legal headaches for retail and restaurant operators. They're often significant dollar amounts and usually resolve faster with legal backing. What did that situation look like?","badResponse":"We handle lease disputes and CAM charge reviews for business owners.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a lease dispute escalated — or your landlord tried to enforce a personal guarantee on a lease you didn't fully understand — what's the personal financial exposure for you as the business owner?","goodResponse":"Personal guarantee enforcement on a commercial lease is one of the fastest ways a business failure becomes a personal financial crisis. Understanding what you signed and having counsel ready to respond is the difference between a business problem and a personal one.","badResponse":"Personal guarantees are serious. Let's make sure yours are handled properly.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If you had an attorney review your current lease and flag any clauses that put you at disproportionate risk — and advise you on your negotiating position for renewal — how would that change your confidence going into the next lease conversation?","goodResponse":"Most business owners are surprised how much negotiating leverage they have at renewal time when they're represented by counsel. Let me walk you through what a commercial lease review looks like and what we typically find.","badResponse":"We do commercial lease reviews for retail and food businesses. It's a flat-fee service.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"Do you have written agreements in place with your key vendors and suppliers — particularly around exclusivity, pricing guarantees, delivery obligations, and what happens if they can't perform?","goodResponse":"Most food and retail businesses run on verbal or email-based supplier relationships, which works fine until a supplier fails to deliver, raises prices unexpectedly, or a dispute over a damaged order comes up with no paper trail. What does your supplier relationship management look like?","badResponse":"We draft vendor and supplier agreements for food and retail businesses.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you ever had a supplier fail to deliver, send a substandard product, or raise prices mid-season in a way that hurt your margins — and had no contractual recourse because the terms weren't written down?","goodResponse":"Supply chain problems are a constant for food and retail operators, and the ones without written terms are the ones who have to absorb the cost. What happened to your margins or operations when that occurred?","badResponse":"Written supplier agreements give you recourse when things go wrong. We draft them.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a key supplier failed during your highest-revenue period — and you couldn't source a replacement in time or recover damages because you had no contract — what does that do to your revenue and your customer relationships?","goodResponse":"Supplier failures during peak season are existential for some food and retail businesses. The legal protection isn't just about recovery — it's about having leverage to prioritize your account and get performance. That leverage comes from the contract.","badResponse":"Supplier failures without contracts are costly. Let's get your agreements in writing.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your critical supplier relationships were governed by written agreements with clear performance standards, pricing terms, and breach remedies — how would that change your operational confidence and your ability to plan inventory and margins?","goodResponse":"Written supplier agreements change the power dynamic in your favor and give you predictability. Let me outline what a standard vendor agreement package looks like for a business at your stage.","badResponse":"We draft vendor agreement packages for food and retail operators. It's usually a small project.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"How are you handling customer-facing liability — do you have terms of service, a liability waiver, or any written documentation that limits your exposure if a customer has an injury, allergic reaction, or product complaint?","goodResponse":"Customer liability exposure for food and retail businesses is very real, and most operators rely entirely on their general liability insurance without any contractual layer. Insurance is important, but it's not the only line of defense. What does your current liability posture look like?","badResponse":"We build the contractual liability protection layer for food and retail businesses.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you ever received a customer complaint, a demand letter, or a social media incident related to an injury or product issue — and found yourself relying entirely on your insurance company to manage the response with no legal strategy of your own?","goodResponse":"Relying entirely on your insurer to manage a customer dispute is common, but insurance companies have their own interests which don't always align with yours — particularly when it comes to admitting fault or setting a precedent. Has any incident gone further than a simple complaint?","badResponse":"We help business owners manage customer liability proactively, not just reactively.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a customer injury or allergic reaction became a lawsuit — and your business had no written terms, waivers, or contractual limitations that your attorney could point to — what's your realistic exposure beyond what your general liability policy covers?","goodResponse":"General liability policies have limits, exclusions, and deductibles. The contractual layer is what determines whether a claim stops at the insurance level or becomes a judgment that follows the business owner personally. That's a meaningful difference.","badResponse":"Liability exposure beyond your insurance policy is the risk most owners don't think about until it's too late.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your business had current terms and conditions, a documented allergen and product disclaimer process, and a simple customer-facing liability framework — how would that change your confidence in handling a serious complaint if one came in tomorrow?","goodResponse":"That preparedness changes how quickly and confidently you can respond, and it signals to plaintiffs' attorneys that you're not an easy target. Let me walk you through what a basic customer liability protection package looks like for a business like yours.","badResponse":"We build customer liability protection documents for food and retail. It's usually a one-time project.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}]],"trades_contractor":[[{"phase":"situation","question":"What does your standard client contract look like for a project — do you have a written scope of work, change order process, and payment schedule spelled out before work starts, or does it vary project to project?","goodResponse":"Contractor disputes almost always trace back to an undefined scope or a verbal change order that one party remembers differently. The contract is your first line of protection. What does your current contract packet include?","badResponse":"We draft contractor agreements with scope, payment, and change order terms that protect you.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you ever had a client refuse to pay, dispute a change order, or claim the work wasn't what they agreed to — and found yourself in a he-said-she-said situation with no written documentation to back you up?","goodResponse":"Payment disputes and scope disagreements are the most common legal headaches contractors face, and they're almost always worse when there's no clear written contract. What happened with your last significant payment dispute?","badResponse":"Written contracts with clear payment terms prevent those disputes. We build them.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a client withheld final payment on a significant project — and you had to choose between absorbing the loss or pursuing it through small claims or a mechanic's lien — what does that do to your cash flow and your ability to take the next job?","goodResponse":"Cash flow disruption from a disputed final payment is one of the fastest ways a profitable contractor ends up in a cash crunch. And filing a mechanic's lien without proper documentation behind it creates its own legal exposure. The contract is what makes the lien solid.","badResponse":"Payment disputes hurt cash flow. Good contracts and lien rights prevent them.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If every client signed a contract that had a clear scope, a change order process, a payment schedule tied to milestones, and a mechanic's lien right built in — how would that change your confidence going into a large project with a new client?","goodResponse":"That documentation gives you leverage, clarity, and a collection tool if things go sideways. Let me walk you through what a standard contractor agreement package covers and how we structure it.","badResponse":"We build contractor agreement packages. It's a flat-fee project that pays for itself on the first dispute you avoid.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"When you bring on subcontractors, do you have a written subcontractor agreement in place — covering scope, payment terms, insurance requirements, and indemnification — before work starts on the jobsite?","goodResponse":"Subcontractor relationships without written agreements are where general contractors take on liability that belongs to the sub. Especially around jobsite injuries and defective work claims, the paperwork determines who's holding the exposure. What does your current sub agreement look like?","badResponse":"We draft subcontractor agreements that protect GCs from liability passed up the chain.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you ever had a subcontractor injury, a defective work claim, or a sub who walked off the job — and found yourself absorbing the liability because the indemnification language in your agreement wasn't strong enough?","goodResponse":"Subcontractor indemnification failures are where GCs get hurt the most. An injury on your jobsite from a sub's employee, or a client's defective work claim that traces to a sub's work — those land on you if the paperwork isn't right. Has anything like that come up?","badResponse":"We write sub agreements with real indemnification teeth so liability stays where it belongs.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a subcontractor injury on one of your jobs resulted in a workers' comp claim and a premises liability suit that named your company — and your sub agreement didn't have proper indemnification — what's the insurance and legal exposure for your business?","goodResponse":"Jobsite injury litigation is expensive and time-consuming even when you win. The difference between a claim that passes through to the sub's insurance versus one that stops at your company is almost entirely determined by your subcontractor agreement language.","badResponse":"Jobsite liability without proper sub agreements is a real exposure. Let's address it.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If every sub on your jobs had signed an agreement with proper indemnification, insurance requirements, and a clear scope of work before the first day — how would that change your confidence and your insurance costs over time?","goodResponse":"Proper sub agreements are one of the most direct ways to reduce your general liability exposure and insurance premiums over time. Let me walk you through a subcontractor agreement template and what the key provisions are.","badResponse":"We build subcontractor agreement packages for GCs and trade contractors. It's a standard engagement.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"Are you structured as an LLC or corporation, and is that entity set up in a way that actually provides personal liability protection — meaning you're maintaining a clear separation between business and personal finances?","goodResponse":"A lot of contractors form an LLC but then run personal expenses through the business, or vice versa, which erodes the liability shield. How long have you been operating under your current entity, and has the structure been reviewed since you set it up?","badResponse":"We review business entity structures and ensure the liability protection is actually working.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you ever had an attorney, accountant, or lender raise questions about your business structure — or had a situation where you weren't sure whether your personal assets were protected if a client sued the business?","goodResponse":"Entity structure confusion is extremely common among contractors who started as a sole proprietor and formed an LLC later without really cleaning up the financial separation. That gap is where personal liability sneaks back in. What prompted you to structure the business the way you did?","badResponse":"We identify the entity structure gaps that leave owners personally exposed.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a client lawsuit successfully pierced the corporate veil — because the line between business and personal finances wasn't clearly maintained — and your personal assets were exposed to a judgment, what would that mean for your family's financial security?","goodResponse":"Veil-piercing is more common in contractor litigation than most business owners realize, especially when the business is owner-operated and the financial separation is informal. The personal exposure is real, and it's almost entirely preventable with proper structure.","badResponse":"Personal asset exposure from your business is a fixable problem. Let's fix it.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your business structure was reviewed, your operating agreement was updated, and your financial separation was verified to be clean — how would that change your confidence when taking on larger projects or more significant clients?","goodResponse":"Clean structure and documented liability protection is also a credibility signal to commercial clients and general contractors who want to know you're running a real business. Let me walk you through what a business structure review looks like.","badResponse":"We do entity structure reviews for contractors. It's a one-time project with lasting protection.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}]],"auto_services":[[{"phase":"situation","question":"When a customer brings in a vehicle and authorizes repair work, what does your authorization and repair order process look like — is it a written document the customer signs, and does it cover your liability for pre-existing conditions or damage discovered during the repair?","goodResponse":"Repair authorization and liability language is where auto service businesses take on significant exposure. A customer who claims new damage or disputes a charge is a lot harder to handle without a clear signed authorization. What does your current repair order say?","badResponse":"We draft repair authorization agreements that protect auto service businesses from liability disputes.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you ever had a customer dispute a repair charge, claim your shop damaged their vehicle, or threaten a chargeback or lawsuit — and found that your written documentation wasn't specific enough to clearly defend your position?","goodResponse":"Customer disputes in auto service almost always come down to documentation. A customer who claims the shop caused damage or didn't complete the work has to contend with clear written evidence of the vehicle's condition at intake and a signed authorization. Has this come up in a significant way?","badResponse":"We write repair authorization terms that make customer disputes much easier to manage.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a customer dispute escalated to a BBB complaint, a credit card chargeback, or a small claims filing — and your paperwork couldn't clearly establish what was authorized and what the vehicle's condition was at drop-off — what does that cost you in time, money, and reputation?","goodResponse":"Chargebacks alone cost auto shops significant money, especially in a volume business. And a small claims appearance costs a full day. The documentation that prevents that is a one-time investment. What's the most time-consuming dispute your shop has dealt with recently?","badResponse":"Disputes without documentation are expensive. Good paperwork prevents most of them.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your repair authorization process included a clear vehicle intake checklist, documented pre-existing conditions, and a signed authorization with liability limitations — how would that change how your service advisors handle disputes?","goodResponse":"Your service advisors go from being on the defensive to being able to confidently show documentation and close disputes quickly. Let me walk you through what a repair authorization and liability documentation package looks like.","badResponse":"We build the intake and authorization documentation for auto shops. It's usually a half-day project.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"If you operate a dealership or sell vehicles — do your purchase agreements, warranty disclaimers, and as-is sale documentation reflect current state lemon law requirements and FTC used car rule compliance?","goodResponse":"Used car rule and lemon law compliance is an area where dealerships and independent sellers face meaningful regulatory exposure, and the forms need to be updated when regulations change. When were your sales documents last reviewed by counsel?","badResponse":"We review dealership and vehicle sales documentation for regulatory compliance.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you ever had a vehicle sale result in a buyer complaint, a state AG inquiry, or a dispute about the vehicle's disclosed condition — where your sales documentation either wasn't complete or the disclosure language wasn't clear enough?","goodResponse":"Vehicle sales disputes that involve disclosure are the ones that escalate fastest to regulatory bodies, and state AGs have been very active in this space. What happened with the situation you're thinking of?","badResponse":"We handle vehicle sale disputes and ensure your disclosures are defensible.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a state regulatory body found that your vehicle sales disclosures weren't compliant — or a buyer successfully argued that they were misled about a vehicle's condition — what's the exposure in terms of fines, rescission orders, or civil liability?","goodResponse":"State AG actions against dealerships and used car sellers have resulted in significant fines and mandatory rescission programs. The cost of a compliance review now is a small fraction of a regulatory enforcement response.","badResponse":"Regulatory exposure in vehicle sales is real. Compliance documentation prevents it.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your vehicle sales documentation — purchase agreements, disclosure forms, warranty disclaimers — was reviewed and updated for current regulatory requirements, how would that change your confidence when processing a high-volume sales month?","goodResponse":"Regulatory confidence in a sales environment means your team can move fast without creating liability. Let me walk you through what a dealership compliance document review looks like.","badResponse":"We do dealership compliance document reviews. It's a focused engagement.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"Do you have employment agreements in place for your technicians and service advisors — specifically covering non-solicitation of customers, confidentiality of your customer list, and the return of any customer data when they leave?","goodResponse":"Auto service businesses build significant value in their customer relationships, and a technician or advisor who leaves and takes those relationships to a competitor is a real threat. What does your current employee paperwork say about customer relationships post-departure?","badResponse":"We draft employment agreements that protect your customer relationships when staff leaves.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you had a long-tenured technician or service advisor leave and take a significant number of loyal customers with them — either to their own shop or to a competitor — without any legal recourse?","goodResponse":"Customer loyalty in auto service follows the person, not the shop, more than in almost any other service business. A trusted advisor who leaves and takes their book with them can represent a meaningful revenue hit. What happened to your customer retention when that person left?","badResponse":"We write non-solicitation agreements that protect customer relationships in auto service.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If losing one high-tenure advisor cost you even 20 percent of your returning customer revenue for the following year — because those customers followed them to their new shop — what's the dollar impact on your annual revenue and your business valuation?","goodResponse":"Repeat customer revenue is the most valuable revenue in auto service — high margin, predictable, and built on trust. Protecting it legally is one of the highest-ROI things a shop owner can do. That math is usually pretty stark when you run it.","badResponse":"Customer loss after staff departures hurts. Non-solicitation agreements help prevent it.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If every key employee at your shop signed an updated agreement with clear non-solicitation language, customer data confidentiality provisions, and proper consideration — how would that change your confidence when investing in training and building customer relationships?","goodResponse":"That protection makes it rational to invest heavily in your team, knowing the customer relationships you're building are protected. Let me walk you through what an auto service employment agreement package looks like.","badResponse":"We build employment agreement packages for auto service businesses. Let's scope it out.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}]],"financial_services":[[{"phase":"situation","question":"When you engage a new advisory or wealth management client, what does your client agreement and disclosure framework look like — specifically your Form ADV disclosures, fee transparency language, and conflict-of-interest documentation?","goodResponse":"Regulatory requirements around advisor disclosures have tightened significantly, and the gap between what firms document and what regulators expect has gotten smaller. When were your client agreements and disclosure documents last reviewed by securities counsel?","badResponse":"We review and update financial advisory client agreements and regulatory disclosures.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you had a client complaint, FINRA inquiry, or SEC exam that surfaced questions about whether your disclosures were sufficient or your fee structures were adequately documented?","goodResponse":"Regulatory exams in financial services are increasingly documentation-intensive, and the most common deficiencies found are in client agreement language and disclosure adequacy. What came up in your last examination cycle?","badResponse":"We prepare firms for regulatory exams and fix disclosure gaps before they become findings.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a regulatory exam resulted in a deficiency letter or a consent order requiring remediation — and your firm had to engage outside securities counsel defensively while also rebuilding documentation — what's the cost to operations and your client relationships?","goodResponse":"Regulatory remediation is expensive in direct legal fees and enormously expensive in management time and client confidence. Proactive documentation review almost always costs less than 10 percent of what a reactive response costs. That's a strong argument for addressing this now.","badResponse":"Regulatory deficiencies are costly. Proactive compliance review is far cheaper.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your client agreements, Form ADV, and conflict-of-interest disclosures were reviewed and updated by securities counsel before your next regulatory exam cycle — how would that change your team's confidence going into that examination?","goodResponse":"Walking into an exam with clean, current documentation changes the entire dynamic of that interaction. Let me walk you through what a financial services compliance document review looks like and what our typical findings are.","badResponse":"We do securities firm compliance document reviews. It's a structured engagement that gives you exam-ready documentation.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"For your insurance products or financial products — do your sales and presentation materials comply with current state insurance regulatory requirements, and have your producer agreements been reviewed for compliance in the states where you operate?","goodResponse":"State insurance regulatory environments vary significantly, and producer agreement requirements and product sales material approval processes differ by state. How many states are your producers currently active in?","badResponse":"We review producer agreements and sales materials for insurance regulatory compliance.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you had a state DOI complaint, a producer licensing issue, or a sales practices investigation that traced back to documentation or disclosure language that wasn't compliant in a specific state?","goodResponse":"State insurance regulators have been particularly active on sales practices and disclosure language, especially for annuity and life insurance products. Multi-state compliance is genuinely complex. What triggered the situation you're describing?","badResponse":"We handle insurance regulatory compliance across states and clean up producer agreement issues.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a state DOI investigation found systemic sales practice violations across multiple producers — resulting in mandatory restitution, producer license suspensions, or a consent agreement — what's the reputational and financial exposure for your organization?","goodResponse":"State DOI consent agreements and the associated remediation are among the most disruptive events for insurance firms — they follow the company's regulatory record for years and affect licensing applications in other states. The downstream cost of one investigation can be substantial.","badResponse":"DOI investigations are expensive and reputationally damaging. Proactive compliance prevents them.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your producer agreements, product disclosures, and sales materials were reviewed and certified compliant across every state you operate in — how would that change your ability to expand into new states or onboard new producers confidently?","goodResponse":"Compliance certification in your current states makes every expansion conversation faster and cleaner. Let me walk you through what a multi-state insurance compliance review looks like and how we structure it.","badResponse":"We do multi-state insurance compliance reviews. It's structured around your active states.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"What does your anti-money laundering and Bank Secrecy Act compliance program look like — do you have a written AML policy, a designated BSA officer, and a current risk assessment, or is that something that's been evolving informally?","goodResponse":"AML and BSA compliance requirements have expanded significantly for financial institutions, and even smaller firms and fintech entities are now subject to meaningful scrutiny. When was your AML program last formally reviewed?","badResponse":"We review and update AML and BSA compliance programs for financial services firms.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you had a FinCEN inquiry, a bank correspondent relationship threatened, or an internal audit finding that suggested your AML program had gaps in customer due diligence, transaction monitoring, or SAR filing procedures?","goodResponse":"Correspondent banking relationships are increasingly being terminated by larger banks due to AML risk concerns, and smaller financial firms are the most affected. A formal program gap finding can be very disruptive. What triggered the issue you're describing?","badResponse":"We identify and close AML program gaps before they create regulatory or banking relationship problems.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If FinCEN or a federal banking regulator found material deficiencies in your AML program — resulting in civil money penalties, a memorandum of understanding, or the requirement to hire a compliance monitor — what's the operational and financial impact on your firm?","goodResponse":"FinCEN civil money penalties have reached tens of millions of dollars for firms with material AML program failures. Compliance monitors are expensive, disruptive, and signal to the market that your institution has serious regulatory problems. Proactive program review is a small investment by comparison.","badResponse":"AML regulatory penalties are severe. A strong program prevents them.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your AML program — written policy, risk assessment, CDD procedures, and training — was reviewed and brought to current regulatory standards, how would that change your confidence in your next examination and your banking relationships?","goodResponse":"A strong, current AML program is a competitive advantage in maintaining correspondent banking relationships and passing regulatory examinations cleanly. Let me outline what an AML program review and gap assessment looks like.","badResponse":"We do AML program reviews and gap analyses for financial services firms. Let's scope the engagement.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}]],"real_estate":[[{"phase":"situation","question":"When you bring on a new agent or broker associate, what does your independent contractor agreement or employment agreement look like — specifically around commission splits, non-solicitation of clients after departure, and ownership of the client database?","goodResponse":"The transition from independent contractor to employee classification is one of the most scrutinized areas in real estate brokerage right now, and the agreements that govern those relationships are critical. What does your current agent agreement say about client ownership?","badResponse":"We draft brokerage agent agreements that protect your book of business and your classification.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you had an agent leave your brokerage and take a significant number of clients or listings directly to a competitor — or to their own new brokerage — without any enforceable non-solicitation to stop it?","goodResponse":"Agent departures in real estate are frequent, and the ones with established client relationships can take meaningful revenue with them. The brokerage's ability to retain those clients almost entirely depends on what the agent agreement says. What happened to your listings when that agent left?","badResponse":"We write agent agreements with non-solicitation terms that protect your brokerage's client relationships.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If an agent who was managing five or six active listings left and moved those listings to another brokerage — and you had no legal mechanism to retain them — what's the GCI impact for your brokerage in that quarter?","goodResponse":"In a brokerage that runs on GCI, losing active listings to a departing agent is an immediate and compounding revenue hit. The cost of proper agreement language is trivial compared to even one deal that walks out the door because the agreement didn't hold.","badResponse":"Listing losses from agent departures hurt GCI directly. Good agreements prevent it.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If every agent at your brokerage signed an updated agreement with enforceable non-solicitation, clear client ownership language, and a structured departure protocol — how would that change your confidence when investing in agent recruitment and training?","goodResponse":"That protection makes it rational to invest heavily in agent development, knowing the client relationships they build belong to the brokerage. Let me walk you through what a brokerage agent agreement review and update looks like.","badResponse":"We build brokerage agent agreement packages. It's a high-ROI engagement for any growing brokerage.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"If you manage investment or commercial properties — do your lease agreements, estoppel certificates, and property management agreements reflect current state landlord-tenant law, and have they been reviewed by counsel in the last couple of years?","goodResponse":"Landlord-tenant law has changed significantly in many states over the last three years — particularly around notice requirements, security deposit handling, and eviction procedures. Agreements that were legally sound before may have gaps now. What markets are your properties in?","badResponse":"We review property management and lease documents for current landlord-tenant law compliance.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you ever had an eviction filing dismissed, a security deposit dispute escalate, or a tenant assert rights under a statute that your lease agreement didn't address properly — leaving you in a weaker legal position than you expected?","goodResponse":"Eviction dismissals because of defective notice or non-compliant lease terms are extremely common in jurisdictions that have tightened tenant protection laws. What did that situation cost you in lost rent and legal fees?","badResponse":"We ensure your lease documentation is legally defensible in the jurisdictions you operate.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a defective lease or improper notice process caused an eviction to fail — and a non-paying tenant stayed in the property for an additional two to four months while you restarted the process — what does that do to your NOI and your relationship with investors or lenders?","goodResponse":"Extended non-paying tenancies from defective eviction processes are one of the most expensive operational failures in property management. And in investor or lender reporting, they raise questions about management quality. The cost of proper documentation is minimal against that exposure.","badResponse":"Failed evictions are expensive. Proper lease documentation prevents them.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your lease agreements, notice forms, and eviction procedures were reviewed and updated for current law in every market you operate in — how would that change your confidence managing problem tenancies and maintaining NOI?","goodResponse":"Clean, current documentation makes your property management operation more professional and more defensible. Let me walk you through what a lease document and eviction procedure review looks like for a portfolio your size.","badResponse":"We do property management document reviews. It's structured by market and portfolio size.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"When you're working as a buyer's agent or a listing agent on a transaction — what does your buyer representation agreement or listing agreement say about your commission protection if the deal changes structure, a buyer goes direct to the seller, or a transaction falls apart and relists?","goodResponse":"Commission protection has become one of the most legally contested areas in real estate following recent NAR settlement changes. The way your representation agreements are written now matters more than it did two years ago. What does your current buyer rep agreement say?","badResponse":"We draft buyer representation and listing agreements that protect agent commission rights under current law.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you lost a commission — or had a commission significantly reduced — because a buyer went around you to work directly with a seller or developer, and your representation agreement wasn't strong enough to enforce your rights?","goodResponse":"Commission protection disputes have increased significantly, and the legal landscape has shifted. The agents who are protected are the ones with representation agreements that are specific about the scope of representation and the commission obligation. Has this come up in the last year or two?","badResponse":"We write representation agreements that actually protect agent commissions under the new legal landscape.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If you spent four to six months working with a buyer who then went direct to a new construction developer — and your representation agreement didn't clearly establish your commission rights in that scenario — what's the GCI you lost, and how does that affect your pipeline for the year?","goodResponse":"A lost new construction commission in a hot market can be $20,000 to $50,000 in a single transaction. Multiply that by the number of buyers you work with, and the value of airtight representation language becomes very clear. That's worth addressing now.","badResponse":"Lost commissions from representation gaps are a real income risk. Better agreements prevent it.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your buyer representation agreement and listing agreement were updated to reflect current law — with clear commission protection language that covers new construction, direct seller contact, and transaction relisting — how would that change your confidence going into every new client relationship?","goodResponse":"Updated representation agreements let you work confidently knowing your income is protected. Let me walk you through what a real estate agent agreement review and update looks like in the current legal environment.","badResponse":"We update real estate representation agreements for the current market and legal landscape. Let's take a look.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}]]};
